Setup

# Core tidyverse
library(tidyverse)

# Text mining
library(tidytext)
library(textdata)   # for NRC and AFINN lexicons

# Tables and visualization polish
library(gt)
library(ggplot2)
library(forcats)
library(scales)
# Read in the raw data
pubmed <- read_csv("pubmed.csv")
pubmed_clean <- pubmed %>%
  mutate(
    abstract_id = row_number(),
    term = str_squish(term),
    abstract = str_squish(abstract)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(abstract), abstract != "")

Text Mining

Question 1

tokens <- pubmed_clean %>%
  unnest_tokens(output = "token", input = abstract, token = "words") %>%
  filter(str_detect(token, "[a-z]"))  # drop pure numbers/punctuation

token_counts <- tokens %>%
  count(term, token, sort = TRUE)

# Abstracts per term
abstracts_per_term <- pubmed_clean %>%
  count(term, name = "n_abstracts") %>%
  arrange(desc(n_abstracts))

Question 2

data("stop_words")  # from tidytext
tokens_nostop <- tokens %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("token" = "word"))

token_counts_nostop <- tokens_nostop %>%
  count(term, token, sort = TRUE)

top5_nostop <- token_counts_nostop %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 5) %>%
  ungroup()

  gt() %>%
  tab_header(title = md("Top 5 tokens per search term (stop words removed)")) %>%

Question 4

# Count tokens per term (stop words already removed)
term_token_counts <- tokens_nostop %>%
  count(term, token, sort = FALSE)

# Calculate TFâIDF
tfidf <- term_token_counts %>%
  bind_tf_idf(token, term, n)

# Top 5 tokens per term by TFâIDF
top5_tfidf <- tfidf %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = tf_idf, n = 5) %>%
  ungroup()

TFâIDF downâweights common words that appear across all abstracts and instead highlights tokens that are uniquely associated with each search term.

Sentiment Analysis

Question 5

nrc <- get_sentiments("nrc")

nrc_counts <- tokens_nostop %>%
  inner_join(nrc, by = c("token" = "word")) %>%
  count(term, sentiment, sort = TRUE)

# Most common sentiment per term
most_common_nrc <- nrc_counts %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 1, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup()

most_common_nrc %>% gt() %>%
  tab_header(title = md("Most common NRC sentiment by search term")) %>%
  fmt_number(columns = n, sep_mark = ",")
Most common NRC sentiment by search term
term sentiment n
covid positive 9,254.00
cystic fibrosis positive 2,564.00
meningitis negative 1,959.00
preeclampsia positive 7,603.00
prostate cancer negative 8,799.00

Answer: Using the NRC lexicon, the most common sentiment for each search term was identified. COVID, cystic fibrosis, and preeclampsia abstracts were considered âpositiveâ sentiment words, while prostate cancer and meningitis abstracts were dominated by ânegativeâ sentiment words. Specifically, COVID had the highest number of positive sentiment tokens (9,254), preeclampsia also showed a strong positive signal (7,603), and cystic fibrosis leaned positive (2,564). In contrast, prostate cancer (8,799) and meningitis (1,959) were most associated with negative sentiment words.Â 

This suggests that while some conditions are described with more positive or neutral biomedical language, others are more often framed in negative contexts, possibly reflecting the severity or clinical framing of those diseases.

Cystic fibrosis abstracts are most associated with disgust, which may reflect language around symptoms or pathology. Lastly, preeclampsia abstracts are dominated by anticipation, likely tied to pregnancyârelated contexts and the forwardâlooking nature of maternal health research.Â 

These results suggest that once general polarity is removed, the NRC lexicon captures more nuanced emotional tones that differ across conditions.

Question 6

afinn <- get_sentiments("afinn")

afinn_scores <- pubmed_clean %>%
  unnest_tokens(output = "token", input = abstract, token = "words") %>%
  inner_join(afinn, by = c("token" = "word")) %>%
  group_by(abstract_id, term) %>%
  summarise(afinn_score = mean(value), .groups = "drop")

glimpse(afinn_scores)

afinn_scores %>%
  mutate(term = fct_infreq(term)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = term, y = afinn_score, fill = term)) +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.3, color = NA) +
  geom_boxplot(width = 0.15, outlier_alpha = 0.3) +

  labs(
    title = "AFINN average positivity scores by search term",
    x = "Search term",
    y = "Mean AFINN score per abstract"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12)

Answer: Using the AFINN lexicon, we calculated the average sentiment score for each abstract. The box-plot visualization shows the distribution of scores by search term. Most abstracts cluster around zero, which indicate largely neutral sentiment overall. However, some conditions show slightly more negative distributions. For example, prostate cancer and meningitis abstracts tend to have more negative scores, while COVID and preeclampsia abstracts show wider variation, with some abstracts leaning more positive. Cystic fibrosis abstracts appear relatively balanced but still center close to neutral.

Overall, the AFINN results suggest that biomedical abstracts are generally written in neutral, technical language, but there are also subtle differences in sentiment emerge which depends on the condition being studied.
